<section class="chapter chapter--deficit" id="deficit-chapter">
    <div class="chapter__content">
        <%- include('layouts/partials/bpToc.ejs', {section: 'deficit'}) %>

        <div class="chapter__flex">
            <div class="chapter__primary">
                <h1 class="chapter__heading--merriweather-font">In 2018,<br>the federal government</br>spent $779 billion more than it collected,
                    <span class="chapter__big-number">resulting in a
                        <span class="chapter__big-number--anecdote-placement">
                            deficit.
                            <section class="anecdote">
                                <h1 class="anecdote__heading">Did you know?</h1>
                                <span class="anecdote__button--text hidden">How can I visualize our Federal Deficit?</span>
                                <div class="anecdote__panes">
                                    <div class="anecdote__pane">
                                        <p>$779 billion is almost <strong>13 times the amount of credit card debt Americans created in 2017</strong> ($61 billion).</p>
                                        <img class="anecdote__illustration" src="assets/bp/deficit/deficit-1.png" alt="">
                                        <p class='source'>Source - <a href='https://www.newyorkfed.org/microeconomics/databank.html' rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Federal Reserve Bank of New York</a></p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="anecdote__pane">
                                        <p>$779 billion breaks down to about <strong>$6,100 of deficit spending</strong> per household in 2018.</p>
                                        <img class="anecdote__illustration" src="assets/bp/deficit/deficit-2.png" alt="">
                                        <p>In 2018, there were an estimated amount of <strong>126 million households</strong> in the United States.</p>
                                        <p class='source'>Source - <a href='https://www.census.gov/popclock/' rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">U.S. Census Bureau</a></p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="anecdote__pane">
                                        <p>$779 billion equates to <strong>$1.5 million</strong> in deficit spending <strong>every minute</strong> for an entire year.</p>
                                        <img class="anecdote__illustration" src="assets/bp/deficit/deficit-3.png" alt="">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="anecdote__cta--container">
                                    <a class="anecdote__cta link-button" href="deficit/">Go Explore Deficit <i class='fa fa-angle-right'></i></a>
                                </div>
                            </section>
                        </span>
                    </span>
                </h1>
                <p class="chapter__paragraph--tightened">The difference between what the federal government collects and what it spends is referred to as a deficit or surplus. In 2018, the federal government spent more than it collected, resulting in a deficit.</p>

                <section class="accordion">
                    <h1 class="accordion__heading">What happens when there is a surplus?</h1>
                    <div class="accordion__content">
                        <p>A surplus occurs when the government collects more money than it spends. The last federal surplus occurred in 2001. The government primarily uses surpluses to reduce the federal debt.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>

