<section class="chapter chapter--debt" id="debt-chapter">
    <div class="chapter__content">
        <%- include('layouts/partials/bpToc.ejs', {section: 'debt'}) %>

        <div class="chapter__flex">
            <div class="chapter__primary">
                <h1 class="chapter__heading--merriweather-font">In 2018,<br>the public debt
                    <span class="chapter__big-number">increased to $21.5
                        <span class="chapter__big-number--anecdote-placement">
                            trillion.
                            <section class="anecdote">
                                <h1 class="anecdote__heading">Did you know?</h1>
                                <span class="anecdote__button--text hidden">How can I visualize our Federal Debt?</span>
                                <div class="anecdote__panes">
                                    <div class="anecdote__pane">
                                        <p>The <strong>National Debt Clock in New York City</strong> estimates the federal debt by second and each household's share. When the clock was installed in 1989, the federal debt was $2.7 trillion.</p>
                                        <img class="anecdote__illustration" src="assets/bp/debt/debt-1.png" alt="">
                                        <p><strong>In 29 years, the national debt has grown by $18.8 trillion.</strong></p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="anecdote__pane">
                                        <p>If the national debt was split evenly among households, <strong>your household's share</strong> would be roughly <strong>$171,000</strong>.</p>
                                        <img class="anecdote__illustration" src="assets/bp/debt/debt-2.png" alt="">
                                        <p>That is about equal to the <strong>median home price in Houston, TX</strong> ($173,600).</p>
                                        <p class='source'>Source - <a href='https://www.census.gov/popclock/' rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">U.S. Census Bureau</a></p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="anecdote__pane">
                                        <p>$21.5 trillion equates to a little more than <strong>$66,000</strong> per individual in the U.S.</p>
                                        <img class="anecdote__illustration" src="assets/bp/debt/debt-3.png" alt="">
                                        <p>That is equal to the <strong>average salary of a Human Resources Specialist</strong>.</p>
                                        <p class='source'>Source - <a href='https://www.bls.gov/oes/current/oes_nat.htm' rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">Bureau of Labor Statistics</a> & <a href='https://www.census.gov/popclock/' rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">U.S. Census Bureau</a></p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="anecdote__cta--container">
                                    <a class="anecdote__cta link-button" href="#">Go Explore Debt <i class='fa fa-angle-right'></i></a>
                                </div>
                            </section>
                        </span>
                    </span>
                </h1>
                <p class="chapter__paragraph--tightened">To pay for a deficit, the federal government usually takes on debt. The total debt outstanding that the federal government owes is essentially the accumulation of deficits over time.</p>
                <p class="chapter__paragraph--tightened">Are federal debt and deficit the same thing? No, but they do affect one another.</p>

                <section class="accordion">
                    <h1 class="accordion__heading">Why can’t the government just print more money?</h1>
                    <div class="accordion__content">
                        <p>“Printing money” is a term that is sometimes used to describe a means of monetary policy. Monetary policy in the United States is conducted by the Federal Reserve. The Federal Reserve uses monetary policy to promote maximum employment, stable prices, and moderate long-term interest rates on the behalf of the Congress. The federal government uses fiscal policy, or the control of taxation and government spending to promote economic activity.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>

